Here is the full **testsmells.org 19-smell academic catalog** audit for `OrderProcessorTests.cs` (MSTest 4.1, .NET 10).

---

## Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell Count | Affected Tests |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| High     | 4           | 4              |
| Medium   | 4           | 3              |
| Low      | 1           | (class-level)  |
| **Total**| **9**       | **7 of 8**     |

Only `ValidateOrder_NullOrder_ThrowsArgumentNullException` is clean.

---

## Findings by Severity

### 🔴 HIGH

**1. Conditional Test Logic** — `ProcessOrder_SetsCorrectStatus` (line 31)

```csharp
if (result.TotalAmount > 100)
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
else
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
```

One branch never executes — the test silently skips it. **Fix:** split into two tests with deterministic inputs:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_OverHundred_SetsPremiumStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-EXPENSIVE", 5) } };
    var result = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory).ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
}

[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_UnderHundred_SetsStandardStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-CHEAP", 1) } };
    var result = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory).ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
}
```

---

**2. Assertion-Free Test (Unknown Test)** — `ProcessOrder_CompletesWithoutError` (line 43)

```csharp
processor.ProcessOrder(order);
// no assertion — passes even if behavior is broken
```

False confidence: this passes as long as no exception is thrown. **Fix:** assert on the expected outcome:

```csharp
var result = processor.ProcessOrder(order);
Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
```

---

**3. Sleepy Test** — `ProcessOrder_AsyncNotification_IsSent` (line 98)

```csharp
Thread.Sleep(2000);
```

Adds 2 seconds of wall-clock time, yet may still be too short on slow CI runners. **Fix:** use a polling/signaling pattern:

```csharp
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
while (!_email.WasNotificationSent(order.Id))
{
    await Task.Delay(50, cts.Token);
}
Assert.IsTrue(_email.WasNotificationSent(order.Id));
```

Or better yet, make `FakeEmailSender` expose a `TaskCompletionSource` you can `await`.

---

**4. Mystery Guest** — `ImportOrders_FromCsv_ParsesCorrectly` (line 144)

```csharp
File.ReadAllText(@"C:\TestData\orders.csv")
```

Hard-coded absolute path to an external file. Test fails on any machine that doesn't have this file. **Fix:** inline the test data:

```csharp
var csv = "SKU,Qty\nSKU-1,2\nSKU-2,1\nSKU-3,3\nSKU-4,1\nSKU-5,5";
var orders = processor.ImportOrders(csv);
Assert.AreEqual(5, orders.Count);
```

